    {
      "source": "evaluator",
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm editing a biology paper and i keep seeing a lot of passive voice. can u explain how to spot it and how i should actually fix it so the sentences are more direct?"
    },
    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Passive voice can be a bit of a sneaky thing, but spotting it is relatively straightforward. It's a bit like a goblin hiding in the shadows - you have to know where to look. Look for verbs that have 'to be' (am, is, are, was, were) followed by a past participle (e.g., been, been, been). These are the telltale signs of passive voice. \n\nFor example, 'The experiment was conducted by John' is passive, whereas 'John conducted the experiment' is active. In the first sentence, the focus is on the experiment, not on John. In the second sentence, John is the one doing the action, making it more direct and engaging. \n\nTo fix passive voice, try rephrasing the sentence to make the subject (the person or thing performing the action) more prominent. This is often referred to as 'inverting the sentence'. For instance, 'The results were analyzed by the research team' becomes 'The research team analyzed the results'. This makes the sentence more concise and easier to read.",
